<subSubSection lastPageId="52" lastPageNumber="53" pageId="51" pageNumber="52" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="51.[151,1436,1907,2011]" lastBlockId="52.[151,1436,152,912]" lastPageId="52" lastPageNumber="53" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,326,1907,1933]" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Body yellowish to reddish brown, shining. Length of pronotum + elytra = 2.8–3.5 mm (males), 2.7–3.2 mm (females). Head densely punctate, punctures larger than those of pronotum. Pronotum widest at basal two-fifths; sides weakly, obtusely rounded at basal two-fifths; basal angles obtuse; broad, ratio length:width = 1:1.7; finely punctate with faint, reticulate microsculpture. Elytra wider than pronotum, ratio length:width = 1:0.75; with 9 regular, closely punctate striae; striae 6 and 7 do not reach apex, stria 8 does not reach base, stria 1 weakly impressed; intervals with scattered minute punctures, transversely striolate. Antennal club (
<figureCitation box="[332,431,268,294]" captionStart="FIGURES 143–147" captionStartId="51.[151,271,1764,1788]" captionTargetBox="[258,1326,970,1740]" captionTargetId="figure-326@51.[254,1332,964,1740]" captionTargetPageId="51" captionText="FIGURES 143–147. Platyhydnobius arizonensis. 143. Right antenna, dorsal view. 144. Mandibles, dorsal view. 145. Aedeagus, dorsal view. 146. Female sternite 8, ventral view. 147. Female coxites and styli, ventral view. Scale bar = 0.3 mm (Figs. 145, 147), 0.4 mm (Fig. 146), 0.5 mm (Figs. 143, 144)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5310991" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5310991/files/figure.png" pageId="52" pageNumber="53">Fig. 143</figureCitation>
) moderately broad, ratio club width:length = 1:2.9; width ratio of antennomeres 7:8:9 = 1.5:1:2.0. Mandibles (
<figureCitation box="[444,547,306,332]" captionStart="FIGURES 143–147" captionStartId="51.[151,271,1764,1788]" captionTargetBox="[258,1326,970,1740]" captionTargetId="figure-326@51.[254,1332,964,1740]" captionTargetPageId="51" captionText="FIGURES 143–147. Platyhydnobius arizonensis. 143. Right antenna, dorsal view. 144. Mandibles, dorsal view. 145. Aedeagus, dorsal view. 146. Female sternite 8, ventral view. 147. Female coxites and styli, ventral view. Scale bar = 0.3 mm (Figs. 145, 147), 0.4 mm (Fig. 146), 0.5 mm (Figs. 143, 144)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5310991" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5310991/files/figure.png" pageId="52" pageNumber="53">Fig. 144</figureCitation>
) moderately elongate, a thin plate forming inner margin apically. In both sexes, all femora unarmed; all tibiae slender, spinose on outer margin, protibiae and mesotibiae weakly widened apically, male mesotibia weakly curved. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[733,803,383,409]" pageId="52" pageNumber="53">Male.</emphasis>
Aedeagus (
<figureCitation box="[942,1042,384,410]" captionStart="FIGURES 143–147" captionStartId="51.[151,271,1764,1788]" captionTargetBox="[258,1326,970,1740]" captionTargetId="figure-326@51.[254,1332,964,1740]" captionTargetPageId="51" captionText="FIGURES 143–147. Platyhydnobius arizonensis. 143. Right antenna, dorsal view. 144. Mandibles, dorsal view. 145. Aedeagus, dorsal view. 146. Female sternite 8, ventral view. 147. Female coxites and styli, ventral view. Scale bar = 0.3 mm (Figs. 145, 147), 0.4 mm (Fig. 146), 0.5 mm (Figs. 143, 144)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5310991" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5310991/files/figure.png" pageId="52" pageNumber="53">Fig. 145</figureCitation>
) with median lobe elongate, apex evenly narrowed. Parameres longer than median lobe, with small lobes laterally near base, flat, apices expanded, thin, with two setae dorsally before apex and many small setae covering apices. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1238,1337,461,487]" pageId="52" pageNumber="53">Female.</emphasis>
Coxites (
<figureCitation box="[159,260,500,526]" captionStart="FIGURES 143–147" captionStartId="51.[151,271,1764,1788]" captionTargetBox="[258,1326,970,1740]" captionTargetId="figure-326@51.[254,1332,964,1740]" captionTargetPageId="51" captionText="FIGURES 143–147. Platyhydnobius arizonensis. 143. Right antenna, dorsal view. 144. Mandibles, dorsal view. 145. Aedeagus, dorsal view. 146. Female sternite 8, ventral view. 147. Female coxites and styli, ventral view. Scale bar = 0.3 mm (Figs. 145, 147), 0.4 mm (Fig. 146), 0.5 mm (Figs. 143, 144)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5310991" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5310991/files/figure.png" pageId="52" pageNumber="53">Fig. 147</figureCitation>
) moderately elongate, cylindrical, with apical and subapical setae; styli elongate, inserted at apices of coxites. Sternite 8 (
<figureCitation box="[409,509,538,564]" captionStart="FIGURES 143–147" captionStartId="51.[151,271,1764,1788]" captionTargetBox="[258,1326,970,1740]" captionTargetId="figure-326@51.[254,1332,964,1740]" captionTargetPageId="51" captionText="FIGURES 143–147. Platyhydnobius arizonensis. 143. Right antenna, dorsal view. 144. Mandibles, dorsal view. 145. Aedeagus, dorsal view. 146. Female sternite 8, ventral view. 147. Female coxites and styli, ventral view. Scale bar = 0.3 mm (Figs. 145, 147), 0.4 mm (Fig. 146), 0.5 mm (Figs. 143, 144)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5310991" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5310991/files/figure.png" pageId="52" pageNumber="53">Fig. 146</figureCitation>
) rounded apically; anterior apophysis broad, apex rounded.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="52" pageNumber="53" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="52.[151,1436,152,912]" pageId="52" pageNumber="53">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,359,576,602]" pageId="52" pageNumber="53">Distribution.</emphasis>
The species occurs across forested northern North America and seemingly with at least one disjunct population in the south in the montane forests of Mount Graham, Arizona (
<figureCitation box="[1148,1252,616,642]" captionStart="FIGURE 148" captionStartId="52.[151,255,1864,1888]" captionTargetBox="[232,1354,970,1837]" captionTargetId="figure-325@52.[232,1354,970,1837]" captionTargetPageId="52" captionText="FIGURE 148. Known North American localities of Platyhydnobius arizonensis (black dots) and P. validus (open squares)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5310994" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5310994/files/figure.png" pageId="52" pageNumber="53">Fig. 148</figureCitation>
). We have seen specimens from 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[355,466,654,680]" pageId="52" pageNumber="53">
<collectingCountry box="[355,461,654,680]" name="Canada" pageId="52" pageNumber="53">Canada</collectingCountry>
:
</emphasis>
the provinces of 
<collectingRegion box="[684,779,654,680]" country="Canada" name="Alberta" pageId="52" pageNumber="53">Alberta</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion box="[792,1008,654,680]" country="Canada" name="British Columbia" pageId="52" pageNumber="53">British Columbia</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion box="[1022,1142,654,680]" country="Canada" name="Manitoba" pageId="52" pageNumber="53">Manitoba</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion box="[1156,1357,654,680]" country="Canada" name="New Brunswick" pageId="52" pageNumber="53">New Brunswick</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion country="Canada" name="Nova Scotia" pageId="52" pageNumber="53">Nova Scotia</collectingRegion>
, Newfoundland, 
<collectingRegion box="[434,528,693,719]" country="Canada" name="Ontario" pageId="52" pageNumber="53">Ontario</collectingRegion>
, and 
<collectingRegion box="[592,687,693,719]" country="Canada" name="Quebec" pageId="52" pageNumber="53">Quebec</collectingRegion>
; 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[700,768,693,719]" pageId="52" pageNumber="53">
<collectingCountry box="[700,763,693,719]" name="United States of America" pageId="52" pageNumber="53">USA</collectingCountry>
:
</emphasis>
the states of 
<collectingRegion box="[930,1012,693,719]" country="United States of America" name="Alaska" pageId="52" pageNumber="53">Alaska</collectingRegion>
and 
<collectingRegion box="[1072,1171,693,719]" country="United States of America" name="Arizona" pageId="52" pageNumber="53">Arizona</collectingRegion>
. The absence of other records in the United States is puzzling.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="52.[151,1436,152,912]" pageId="52" pageNumber="53">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,506,770,796]" pageId="52" pageNumber="53">Field notes and habitats.</emphasis>
Adults have been collected in mixed deciduous and coniferous forest habitats, most frquently with flight interecept traps and a few by evening car netting and in litter sifting.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="52.[151,1436,152,912]" pageId="52" pageNumber="53">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,346,847,873]" pageId="52" pageNumber="53">Seasonality.</emphasis>
Adults have been collected in the months of June to October, with the greatest numbers in July (93) and August (133).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
